post_text:
Parents of WN Seniors

According to Indiana State Law, PRIOR to beginning their senior year, students are supposed to have a second MCV (meningococcal) vaccine, and 2 doses of Hepatitis A vaccine. Due to all of the recent issues with COVID, many seniors were unable to get these immunizations. On Sept. 28th, the Noble County Health Dept. will be coming to West Noble during the school day to administer these vaccines. If you are interested in an information packet, please have your student pick one up in the nurse's office. If you are unsure if your student still needs these vaccines, contact Nurse Robin at 260-894-3191 ext. 3040.

CONSENT FORMS are due back by AUGUST 31ST.

CHARGE Back to School is tomorrow!! We hope to see you at this drive-through back to school event on August 6 from 3-7 pm. We are ready to help your family have a successful start to the school year with school supplies, water bottles, fresh and non-perishable food, hygiene supplies, and thermometers. Come check it out so your student can CHARGE Back to School!!

Estamos listos para ayudar a su familia a comenzar con éxito el año escolar con útiles escolares, botellas de agua, alimentos frescos y no perecederos, suministros de higiene y termómetros. Ven a verlo para que tu estudiante esté preparado para regresar a clases.

post_text: Our West Noble community is strong and compassionate. Right now, some of our finest people are battling illness. We want to surround these people and their families with prayer, love, and support. West Noble School Corporation is encouraging all community members to wear Charger Gear this Friday, April 3 to stand behind those who are currently fighting sickness. Please take a picture in your Charger attire (Red & Blue) and post it on social media (Facebook, Instagram, Twitter). You also may choose to hold a ¨Get Well" sign. Please include the hashtag #ChargerStrong so everyone can search for these photos. We are blessed to be in such a strong community!

Good afternoon.

At Governor Holcomb's press conference this afternoon, he announced that all Indiana Schools are closed until May 1. He also stated that all Spring testing (ILEARN, ISTEP, IREAD 3) are canceled. More information will be coming to you as it becomes available.

Therefore:
1. All West Noble Schools are now closed until May 1.
2. All Spring Testing is canceled.
3. School Meals will begin Wednesday, March 25th.”

WNMS Families,

Good afternoon to all of our Charger Families. This has been an unsettling week for us all.

Due to the unstable nature of current events, all of our previously scheduled school events have been postponed. We plan to return to school on April 27. At the time of our return, we will reschedule as many of our events as we can.

Each Monday we will release a newsletter containing activities and academic challenges for our students. Be sure to check Google Classroom for additional postings from your student's teachers.

post_text:
ALL HS Parents/Students:

On April 17, during the school day, the Noble County Health Dept. will be at the high school to administer immunizations. All students who are going to be SENIORS this August will need to have their second MCV (meningococcal vaccine) prior to school starting.

A NEW MANDATE is that ALL students in grades 9-12 next year must also have two doses of Hepatitis A prior to the 2020-2021 school year.

If you would like to have your student receive his/her vaccines at the clinic being held at the high school, please pick up/have your student pick up a consent form in the nurse's office. Completed forms are due back by March 27, 2020.

If you are unsure whether or not your student has already gotten these shots, please contact Nurse Robin at 260-894-3191 ext. 3040.

post_text:
As we continue to make our way through the cold and flu season and now face the uncertainty of Covid-19, it is good to remember four basic measures to stay healthy:

1. Wash your hands frequently and thoroughly. Good handwashing requires soap and water, lasts at least 20 seconds, and covers every surface of your hands.

2. Cough or sneeze into your elbow. Not into your hand. Not into the air.

3. Keep your hands away from your face. Germs enter through your mouth, nose, and eyes.

4. Stay home if you have symptoms of illness. Students should not return to school after illness until they are fever-free for 24 hours without medication. This will be strictly enforced by our nurses.

post_text: It is that time of year when colds, flu, and stomach viruses are very common, and this year is no different. Our school nurses are seeing an uptick in illnesses, but nothing alarming. Rest assured, we monitor attendance closely and are far below the health department notification rate of 20% absences due to illness. However; local healthcare providers are reporting a high level of Influenza B with symptoms of fever, headache, aching, and cough. This can be treated with Tamiflu if diagnosed early. It is also not too late to get a flu shot for yourself or your children which can prevent or dramatically reduce the symptoms of the flu. As always, wash your hands frequently and keep students home if they have a temperature over 100 degrees until they are fever-free for 24 hours without medication.

post_text:
HS Students and Parents - Immunization Requirements Change

Due to changes to Indiana State Law, beginning in August 2020 (next school year), ALL HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS (GRADES 9-12) are REQUIRED to have two doses of Hepatitis A vaccine.

Since the two doses of the immunization must be given at least 6 months apart, if your student has not received this vaccine yet, NOW would be a great time to make an appointment for the first dose.

***Prior to entering 12th grade, students must also have a second dose of the MCV (meningococcal) vaccine. Students may receive this any time after they turn 16 years of age. Therefore, if he/she is old enough when they get their Hep A immunization, you may go ahead and have them get the MCV at the same time.

If you need to check if your student has received one or both of the above immunizations, you may call Nurse Robin at the HS (ext. 3040), or call the office where your student receives his/her vaccines.

post_text: In order to support West Noble teachers who wish to take part in the ISTA’s Red for Ed day, West Noble Schools will be closed on Tuesday, November 19, 2019. The number of staff members planning to attend this event is high enough that securing sufficient substitute teachers for the day is not feasible. The make-up day will be on Thursday, May 21, 2020. Traditional public schools in Indiana have not been adequately funded, while charter schools and vouchers have seen continued increases in funding. The focus for the day is to stand up for better funding for all traditional public schools, to keep class sizes at manageable levels, and to ensure that students can and will receive the best instruction by qualified and certified classroom teachers.

Registration is open for the 19-20 school year. Please register as soon as possible. Registering students online requires their SnapCode. For student information security, a new and unique SnapCode is required for each student each year. If you did not receive your SnapCode please contact the school via email at wnstudentinfo@westnoble.k12.in.us and request your SnapCode.

If you have your student(s) SnapCode and you are ready to register online, please proceed to https://www.westnoble.k12.in.us/Content2/4 and select the online version (English or Spanish) you need.

If you are NEW to West Noble you can register during the CHARGE Back to School event on Thursday, August 1st, from 12 to 7 pm at the high school. Please bring the following: transcript from your previous school, birth certificate, immunization record, and proof of residency.

See you soon!

post_text:
On Thursday, August 1 from 12:00-7:00 pm West Noble is holding its first CHARGE Back to school event. This event is a community fair designed to make sure West Noble students have everything they need for a successful start to the school year.

Participants will also have the opportunity to visit the health department nurse for immunizations, get a free haircut, and pick up food, hygiene items, clothing and school supply items provided by various agencies.

In addition, families will be able to sign up for free/reduced lunch, have a child ID printed through the police department, and sign up for Hoosier Healthwise (Medicaid). Numerous social service organizations will be on site to discuss the services they provide and answer questions.

Besides providing lots of resources to help you CHARGE Back to School, there will be fun activities for kids and families, as well as free popcorn and water. Charger gear will be available while supplies last, and practical door prizes will be given out throughout the event.

See you there!

Reminder:
The mobile dentists will be at the high school and middle school on Wednesday, January 30. Visit https://www.myschooldentist.com to sign up your middle or high school student today.

Dental care is usually at no cost to you. All insurance is accepted including Medicaid and Hoosier Healthwise. A low-cost self-pay option is available for those without insurance.

Convenient and comfortable: Our in-school dental program saves you time and provides a safe and comfortable place for your child to receive gentle dental care from licensed local professionals. Dental care includes a complete dental exam, x-rays, cleaning, fluoride and sealants when necessary, and in some cases, restorative care such as fillings.

Questions: Contact your building school nurse.

post_text:
Upcoming ISTEP Testing Information (11th and 12th grade)

ISTEP re-tests will be for any 11th or 12th-grade student who has not passed either the English or Math tests. Testing will be from 8:15 until 10:15 on the six dates listed below. Any 11th or 12th-grade student who has passed may report to school by 10:15 for classes, and we will follow our two-hour delay schedule. Students who have not passed will report to school by 8:15 for testing. Buses will run at the normal time. Non-testing students who cannot find a way to school by 10:15 may ride the bus at their normal pick up time and we will provide study time in our LRC.

English Testing Dates
Tuesday, Nov 27th
Wednesday, Nov 28th
Thursday, Nov 29th

Math Testing Dates
Tuesday, Dec 4th
Wednesday, Dec 5th
Thursday, Dec 6th

Students who have not passed will report to school by 8:15 for testing. Buses will run at the normal time. Non-testing students who cannot find a way to school by 10:15 may ride the bus at their normal pick up time and we will provide study time in our LRC.

English Testing Dates
Tuesday, Nov 27th
Wednesday, Nov 28th
Thursday, Nov 29th

Math Testing Dates
Tuesday, Dec 4th
Wednesday, Dec 5th
Thursday, Dec 6th

Over 65 students from 7 area schools are participating in a week-long summer camp with the Young Americans at Central Noble High School. Approximately 20 of them are West Noble students!

The Young Americans were here last fall for a workshop, and were able to come back for a week-long summer camp.

Students will be participating in singing, acting, dancing and performing workshops all week. There will be a final performance Saturday, June 9th at 6:30 P.M. at the Central Noble High School Auditorium.

Doors open at 6:00 PM. Tickets are $12 for adults and $10 for students.

post_text:
The Certificate of Multilingual Proficiency serves to certify the attainment of proficiency in multiple languages by students for employers and universities. It is a statement of accomplishment that helps to signal evidence of a student’s readiness for career and college, and for engagement as a global citizen. The focus is on achieving the level of proficiency required for English and the level of proficiency required for one or more other languages. Congratulations to these WNHS students who will be graduating with the certificate!
